entry.title: Respect filters for internal intersection observers
entry.content:
Though the IntersectionObserver V1 spec says not to respect filters,

some internal intersection observers specifically require to respect

filters (e.g.

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-contain-2/#:~:text=If%20a%20filter).



This CL is kept small by reverting crrev.com/c/4960480 for all

internal intersection observers. Ideally we should allow each

internal intersection observer to decide whether to respect filters,

which will be done later.



This CL also removes the IntersectionObserverIgnoreFilters flag, and

make the behavior of js IntersectionObserver ignoring filters

permanent.

entry.title: [Android][CredMan] Split CreateCredentialRequest responsibilities
entry.content:
This CL introduces

1- CredManRequestDecorator interface. The interface is used for

extending Bundles and CreateCredentialRequest.Builder members. Future

CLs will include other requests (GetCredentialRequest) in the

interface.

1- GpmCredManRequestDecorator: This interface is used by the browser

to control CredMan flags and talk to Gpm.

1- CreateCredentialRequestHelper: The class is responsible for

creating a base CreateCredentialRequest. It will delegate the further

modifications to a GpmCredManRequestDecorator.



Future CLs will introduce other decorators (e.g. non-browser) and

other request helpers (e.g. GetCredentialRequestHelper).

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Keep the default suggestion fixed to search or non-search
entry.content:
go/autocomplete-controller-refactor has some details on the refactor

plan.



This is part 6 of the refactor.



ML tries to keep the ranking of searches and URLs fixed. It's allowed to

rerank URLs among themselves, but not move them relative to searches.



However, due to not considering `allowed_to_be_default`, it can cause

the default suggestion to swap from a search to a URL or vice versa when

it picks a top URL suggestion that is|isn't allowed to be default and

the traditional scoring picked a top URL suggestion that wasn't|was

allowed to be default).



This CL fixes this. If the default suggestion was a search|URL with

traditional ranking, then it will remain a search|URL with ML ranking.



The fix is in `AutocompleteController::RunBatchUrlScoringModel()`.

Before, we collected the URL scores, and redistributed them according to

ML ranking; the highest ML ranked URL would get the highest traditional

URL score. Likewise, we redistributed shortcut boosting, the N highest

ML ranked suggestions would get boosted.



With this CL, the new approach is



1. Sort the suggestions according to traditional ranking.

2. Check whether the default suggestion is a URL or search.

3. Check the # of URLs above searches (i.e. shortcut boosting) other

than the default suggestion. Not counting the default match ensures

the # of URLs-boosted-above-searches remains the same even if the

traditional default match was a boosted shortcut that is no longer

default with ML ranking.

4. If the traditional default was a URL, find the new top-ML-ranked and

`allowed_to_be_default` match and assign it the highest traditional

score. Picking an `allowed_to_be_default` match ensures ensures the

default suggestion won't switch from a URL to a search.

5. Otherwise, if the traditional default was a search, cap the pool of

scores below the default search's score; this ensures the default

suggestion won't switch from a search to a URL.

6. Reassign shortcut boosting and relevance scores.



This change is param guarded: `stable_search_ranking`. The original

`RunBatchUrlScoringModel()` is left in the code in case we decide to

launch before we've experimented with this fix.



This CL also extracts `AutocompleteResult::Sort()` from

`AutocompleteResult::SortAndCull()` so that the former can be called

independently. This is needed to determine the default match without

wasting effort on the cull and other post processing steps. This is only

needed for the short term until we have ML search ranking, after which,

we won't need to preserve the default match type.



This CL also removes the `ml_url_scoring_rerank_final_matches_only` code

paths. They're not launch-likely and I didn't want to worry updating

entry.title: In-effect animations should force a stacking context
entry.content:
An in-effect animation includes those that are in the before or after

phase with the animation having the corresponding fill. Per spec[1],

such animations should have a side-effect of being equivalent to having

`will-change` set to the target property.



https://crrev.com/46005e74c changed opacity animations to no longer have

clamp to a value below exactly 1. It turns out having a non-1 value was

what was causing opacity animations to force a stacking context; the

animation effect was only considered to be affecting a property if the

effect was current.



This CL updates the 'affecting' state to include animations that are in

effect.



[1] https://drafts.csswg.org/web-animations-1/#side-effects-section
